[The hantavirus involved in the case above is not mentioned, but very likely is Andes virus, as was confirmed in the Epuyen outbreak earlier this year (2019). The Andes virus (ANDV, genus _Orthohantavirus_, family Hantaviridae) was confirmed as the etiological agent in the Epuyen outbreak. Its most common host reservoir is the long-tailed pygmy rice rat (_Oligoryzomys longicaudatus_).

Transmission from rodent to human usually occurs through close contact with infected urine and excretions. Secondary human-to-human infections are considered rare but may occur through direct contact with infected saliva, urine, or blood. However, in the situation above, because of the human-to-human transmission in the Epuyen outbreak, the patient's wife and daughter have been placed in isolation until proven free of infection, or treated if infected. - Mod.TY

